1
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:09,400
(WHISTLING)

2
00:00:17,400 --> 00:00:19,760
River! I'll see you later!

3
00:00:20,120 --> 00:00:23,480
Tell Marilyn she's too late,
she'll have to use the biplane.

4
00:00:23,560 --> 00:00:24,880
Take care.

5
00:00:28,560 --> 00:00:29,960
(BUZZING)

6
00:00:36,120 --> 00:00:37,840
-Do you do this every night?
-Oh!

7
00:00:38,640 --> 00:00:41,320
-Hello.
-You're trying to conceal a euphonium.

8
00:00:41,400 --> 00:00:43,280
Guiltily. Has that ever been
attempted before?

9
00:00:43,360 --> 00:00:45,680
What? Oh, this. Oh, yeah,

10
00:00:45,800 --> 00:00:48,560
it's just one of those euphoniums.

11
00:00:48,640 --> 00:00:52,240
Okay, so is this what you do at night
when we're sleeping?

12
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:53,720
Have extra adventures?

13
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:55,560
I don't sleep as much as you.
I keep busy.

14
00:00:55,640 --> 00:00:58,560
-Doing what? Actually, tell me for once.
-(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

15
00:00:58,760 --> 00:01:02,400
You're my friend, my best friend.
So tell me what it is you do.

16
00:01:04,920 --> 00:01:08,200
Okay. I just helped out a possessed
orchestra on a moon base.

17
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:09,920
Before that, I prevented two supernovas,

18
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:11,600
wrote a history of the universe,
all in jokes,

19
00:01:12,000 --> 00:01:14,280
and did a bit of locum work in Brixton.

20
00:01:15,040 --> 00:01:17,560
Lovely practice, very short-staffed.

21
00:01:21,480 --> 00:01:22,640
What's wrong?

22
00:01:23,840 --> 00:01:27,000
We're all such tiny parts of your life,
aren't we?

23
00:01:28,160 --> 00:01:30,520
All the friends you make
just flicker in and out.

24
00:01:30,600 --> 00:01:32,040
You must hardly notice us.

25
00:01:34,440 --> 00:01:35,440
Amy,

26
00:01:36,320 --> 00:01:38,480
you are enormous parts of my life.

27
00:01:39,360 --> 00:01:41,640
And you are all I ever remember.

28
00:01:44,080 --> 00:01:45,400
Speaking of which...

29
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:52,040
-My life doesn't make any sense.
-I know.

30
00:01:52,480 --> 00:01:55,680
That's what I've been trying
to talk to you about.

31
00:01:56,280 --> 00:01:57,480
I know.

32
00:01:58,160 --> 00:01:59,160
Now,

33
00:02:00,280 --> 00:02:02,640
when I first met you,
I didn't have parents.

34
00:02:02,720 --> 00:02:04,360
I never had parents.

35
00:02:04,440 --> 00:02:06,280
And then you did whatever it was you did

36
00:02:06,360 --> 00:02:08,920
and rebooted the universe
and suddenly, I...

37
00:02:09,920 --> 00:02:11,400
had parents.

38
00:02:11,840 --> 00:02:13,400
And I've always had parents.

39
00:02:13,520 --> 00:02:15,520
And I remember both lives in my head,

40
00:02:15,600 --> 00:02:17,920
both of them in my head
at the same time.

41
00:02:18,160 --> 00:02:20,360
-And it's fine, isn't it?
-Yeah, but it shouldn't be.

42
00:02:20,440 --> 00:02:23,120
-Why is it fine?
-Rory was a Roman for 2,000 years.

43
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:24,320
He says he hardly remembers it.

44
00:02:24,520 --> 00:02:27,440
Ah, but sometimes you
catch him just staring.

45
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:30,040
The thing is, Amy,

46
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:33,640
everyone's memory is a mess.
Life is a mess.

47
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:37,280
Everyone's got memories of a holiday
they couldn't have been on

48
00:02:37,360 --> 00:02:39,200
or a party they never went to,

49
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:40,600
or met someone for the first time

50
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:43,280
and felt like they've
known them all their lives.

51
00:02:43,360 --> 00:02:46,240
Time is being rewritten all around us,
every day.

52
00:02:46,400 --> 00:02:50,360
People think their memories are bad,
but their memories are fine.

53
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:53,880
The past is really like that.

54
00:02:55,560 --> 00:02:58,560
-That's ridiculous.
-Yeah, now you're starting to get it.

55
00:02:59,400 --> 00:03:01,440
-Put your hand here.
-What is it?

56
00:03:01,520 --> 00:03:03,000
Tardis telepathic circuits.

57
00:03:03,080 --> 00:03:05,560
-What do I do?
-Nothing, just relax.

58
00:03:06,480 --> 00:03:09,720
Your saddest ever memory was at
a fairground in 1994.

59
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:12,640
-Can you remember why?
-No. Hang on, did I...

60
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:16,360
Did I drop an ice cream?
That can't be my saddest memory.

61
00:03:16,680 --> 00:03:18,520
-Remembering ice cream's always sad.
-(WHOOSHING)

62
00:03:18,640 --> 00:03:19,960
(THUDDING)

63
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:22,320
Did we just land? Where are we?

64
00:03:22,560 --> 00:03:24,320
What happened after you
dropped the ice cream?

65
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:25,720
Nothing, I cried.

66
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:31,480
No, no, hang on.
There was a lady and she

67
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:35,160
-bought me another one.
-Good for her. What did she look like?

68
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:37,120
She looked like she...

69
00:03:38,120 --> 00:03:40,800
She had a funny dress, a nightdress.

70
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:42,480
She had red hair.

71
00:03:44,080 --> 00:03:45,200
Doctor...

72
00:03:48,800 --> 00:03:51,880
I don't understand. Why are you
doing this? What is the point?

73
00:03:51,960 --> 00:03:54,040
The nice lady, what did she say to you?

74
00:03:54,480 --> 00:03:55,960
Cheer up. Have an ice cream.

75
00:03:57,480 --> 00:03:58,480
(SIGHS)

76
00:03:58,800 --> 00:04:03,520
Amy, time and space is never ever
going to make any kind of sense.

77
00:04:04,200 --> 00:04:06,240
A long time ago,
you got the best possible advice

78
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:07,520
on how to deal with that.

79
00:04:07,600 --> 00:04:10,800
So, I suggest you go and give it.

80
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:17,800
Okay, okay, so I ask a big,
important question about life

81
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:20,920
and you're basically telling me
to go and buy myself an ice cream.

82
00:04:21,040 --> 00:04:23,440
No, Amy, I am telling you
to go and buy us both ice creams.

83
00:04:23,560 --> 00:04:25,000
-I love fairgrounds.
-I hate you.

84
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:26,080
No, you don't.

85
00:04:26,280 --> 00:04:27,560
Do you get scared on ghost trains?

86
00:04:27,640 --> 00:04:31,080
I get a bit scared.
So is it okay if I hold your hand?

